TY  - JOUR
AU  - Hasbrouck, Joel
T1  - The Summary Informativeness of Stock Trades: An Econometric Analysis
PY  - 1991
Y1  - 1991/07/01
DO  - 10.1093/rfs/4.3.571
JO  - The Review of Financial Studies
JA  - Rev Financ Stud
VL  - 4
IS  - 3
SP  - 571
EP  - 595
SN  - 0893-9454
AB  - In a security market with asymmetrically informed participants, trades are signals of private information. In this article, new measures of trade informativeness are proposed based on a decomposition of the variance of changes in the efficient price into trade-correlated and -uncorrelated components. The trade-correlated component has a natural interpretation as an absolute measure of trade informativeness. The ratio of this component to the total variance is a relative measure (i.e., a proportion normalized with respect to the total public information). For a sample of NYSE-listed companies, trades are found to be more informative for small firms in both absolute and relative senses. From an analysis of intraday patterns, it appears that trades are in absolute terms more informative at the beginning of trading, but slightly less informative in relative terms.
Y2  - 3/26/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1093/rfs/4.3.571
ER  - 



